Your program works correctly and prints all command-line arguments including the program name. Let’s break it down carefully.

1️⃣ Code
#include <stdio.h>
int main(int argc, char *argv[])
{
    while (*argv != NULL)
        printf("%s\n", *(argv++));
    return 0;
}
2️⃣ What argc and argv represent

If you run:

./a.out apple mango banana

Then:

argc = 4

Memory layout:

argv[0] → "./a.out"
argv[1] → "apple"
argv[2] → "mango"
argv[3] → "banana"
argv[4] → NULL

Also:

argv → &argv[0]
3️⃣ Understanding the loop condition
while (*argv != NULL)

*argv means:

value stored at current argv pointer

So it checks:

argv[0], argv[1], argv[2], ...

until it reaches NULL.

4️⃣ Understanding the print statement
printf("%s\n", *(argv++));

Important rule:

argv++  → use current pointer, then increment

So:

*(argv++) == current argument string

Equivalent to:

printf("%s\n", argv[i]);
i++
5️⃣ Step-by-step execution

Initial pointer:

argv → argv[0]
Iteration 1
*argv → "./a.out"
print "./a.out"
argv++
Iteration 2
*argv → "apple"
print "apple"
argv++
Iteration 3
*argv → "mango"
print "mango"
argv++
Iteration 4
*argv → "banana"
print "banana"
argv++
Iteration 5
*argv → NULL
loop stops
6️⃣ Output
./a.out
apple
mango
banana
7️⃣ Equivalent simpler code

Your code is equivalent to:

for(int i = 0; argv[i] != NULL; i++)
    printf("%s\n", argv[i]);
8️⃣ Key concept tested in interviews

Pointer arithmetic:

argv[i] == *(argv + i)

And:

*(argv++) == argv[0], argv[1], argv[2] ...
9️⃣ If you want to skip program name

Use:

while (*++argv != NULL)
    printf("%s\n", *argv);

Output would be:

apple
mango
banana
